This error occurs when you try to access a property or method of an undefined value. In this case, it is likely that you are trying to access the `$scopedSlots` property of an undefined value.

To fix this error, you need to ensure that the value you are accessing is not undefined. You can check for undefined values using an `if` statement or by using optional chaining (in newer versions of JavaScript).

Here's an example using optional chaining:

```
// Before:
const mySlots = myComponent.$scopedSlots;

// After:
const mySlots = myComponent?.$scopedSlots;
```

In this example, the optional chaining `?.` checks if `myComponent` is defined before trying to access its `$scopedSlots` property. If `myComponent` is undefined, `mySlots` will also be undefined (which you can handle accordingly in your code).
